          <h2>The cost of standing still — and the one lever that matters</h2>
          <p class="lede">
            Most planning tools hand you a list: here are ten things you could improve. That's not actually useful — it
            spreads your attention thin across everything that could theoretically be better, and nothing moves.
          </p>
          <p>
            We built this differently, in code. Every stalled project, every plan that isn't moving, every business that
            feels stuck is almost always limited by <strong>one</strong> thing at a time — the single bottleneck actually
            holding it back. Everything else on the list is a distraction from that one thing. We call it the
            <strong>binding constraint</strong>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Standing idly by has a real cost: the plan doesn't move, the same conversation happens again next week, and
            that cost keeps accruing for as long as the real bottleneck goes unnamed. So instead of asking "what could
            be better," our engine asks a narrower question — of everything in your way right now, what is the one thing
            actually stopping progress, how sure are we, and what's the smallest concrete step that tests or relieves
            it?
          </p>
          <p>
            That single answer is your <strong>optimization lever</strong>. Not a to-do list — the one place where
            effort actually moves something, because it's the one place effort was actually being blocked.
